	<section class="page">
<p>In a buyout that dwarfs others, Microsoft <a href="https://news.microsoft.com/2022/01/18/microsoft-to-acquire-activision-blizzard-to-bring-the-joy-and-community-of-gaming-to-everyone-across-every-device/" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">announced plans today</a> to purchase digital game development company <a href="https://www.activisionblizzard.com/" rel="nofollow">Activision Blizzard</a> in an all-cash deal worth $68.7 billion.</p><p>If the acquisition goes through, it would significantly add to Microsoft’s already sizeable video game operation, which includes "Minecraft" and "Doom." Activision’s stable of popular video games includes "Call of Duty," "World of Warcraft," and "Candy Crush" — all of which are already available through Microsoft’s Xbox console business.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/3647294/microsoft-to-buy-video-game-maker-activision-blizzard-for-687b.html#jump">To read this article in full, please click here</a></p></section></article>